0"></use></svg><h1>ROT13</h1><p>This transformation cipher shifts letters 1=
3 places in the alphabet. Generally, we can change the individual character=
s in a <code>string</code> based on logic.</p><svg><use href=3D"b.svg#desig=
n1"></use></svg><p>For this cipher, many implementations are possible. Some=
 are faster than others. Some initialization time may be required. ROT13 he=
lps us learn how to transform strings.</p><svg><use href=3D"b.svg#design2">=
</use></svg><h2>Example</h2><p>In a <code>for</code>-loop, we test each cha=
racter, and add it to a character buffer. We could use <code>StringBuilder<=
/code>, but this would be slower for single character appends.</p><div clas=
s=3D"z"><svg><use href=3D"b.svg#inset"></use></svg><div><b>Tip</b> Be sure =
to evaluate the <code>char</code> lookup table method, which is faster, alt=
hough somewhat more complex.</div></div><div class=3D"z"><svg><use href=3D"=
b.svg#inset"></use></svg><div><b>Detail</b> This method does not store stat=
e, so it is placed in a <code>static</code> <code>class</code>. It calls th=
e <code>ToCharArray</code> method.</div></div><div class=3D"z"><svg><use hr=
ef=3D"b.svg#inset"></use></svg><div><b>Next</b> <code>Transform()</code> ca=
sts the <code>char</code> to an integer and then transforms that value. It =
casts back to a <code>char</code>, and uses the <code>string</code> constru=
ctor.</div></div><div class=3D"Y"><input type=3D"checkbox" id=3D"i3"><label=
